1
00:00:24,124 --> 00:00:26,593
It wasn't so long ago, you know.

2
00:00:26,659 --> 00:00:29,321
People really did
live their lives like that.

3
00:00:29,396 --> 00:00:31,865
That's too stupid for words!

4
00:00:31,931 --> 00:00:34,764
There's an old rhyme
from my childhood.

5
00:00:34,834 --> 00:00:37,963
We used to sing it
when we were your age.

6
00:00:38,038 --> 00:00:41,599
♪ Twinkle, twinkle little star

7
00:00:41,674 --> 00:00:44,769
My dad drives a rusty car ♪

8
00:00:44,844 --> 00:00:48,280
♪ Press the button
Pull the choke, ♪

9
00:00:48,348 --> 00:00:51,443
Off he goes in a cloud of smoke.

10
00:00:51,518 --> 00:00:54,818
♪ Twinkle, twinkle little star

11
00:00:54,888 --> 00:00:59,849
- "♪ My dad drives a rusty car ♪"
- What's a rusty car?

12
00:00:59,926 --> 00:01:02,793
The things they used to have
before they knew better.

13
00:01:02,862 --> 00:01:06,526
- You're too young to know about those things.
- No, I'm not!

14
00:01:06,599 --> 00:01:11,366
- I'm a big kid.
- Yes, you're a big kid, but you can't know everything yet.

15
00:01:13,807 --> 00:01:15,741
But the point of the rhyme...

16
00:01:15,809 --> 00:01:20,076
is what happened next.

17
00:01:20,146 --> 00:01:23,878
- What did happen next?
- Look.

18
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:28,820
Look up there.

19
00:01:28,888 --> 00:01:31,550
There's the Southern Cross.

20
00:01:31,624 --> 00:01:33,854
That group of five stars there.

21
00:01:33,927 --> 00:01:36,362
The small one Is Epsilon.

22
00:01:36,429 --> 00:01:40,764
Which small one?
I can't see it.

23
00:01:40,834 --> 00:01:44,464
It's the fifth one, the
one that's not as bright as the other four.

24
00:01:44,537 --> 00:01:46,471
That's Epsilon.

25
00:01:46,539 --> 00:01:48,769
I see it.

26
00:01:51,644 --> 00:01:53,635
I can't.

27
00:01:53,713 --> 00:01:58,810
- What's so special about it?
- I'm trying to recall.

28
00:01:58,885 --> 00:02:02,947
Forty years is along time.

29
00:02:03,022 --> 00:02:07,357
I met Aim
on a night like this one.

30
00:02:08,561 --> 00:02:13,556
No moon, cool and clear.

31
00:02:13,633 --> 00:02:16,102
He was just a man
wandering in the desert,

32
00:02:16,169 --> 00:02:19,537
miles from anywhere.

33
00:02:19,606 --> 00:02:22,803
Walking, wandering.

34
00:02:22,876 --> 00:02:26,073
Had been for days.

35
00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:30,174
He stumbled across my campsite
by accident.

36
00:02:30,250 --> 00:02:34,346
I gave him something to eat,
something to drink...

37
00:02:34,420 --> 00:02:39,381
and he told me
the most fantastic story.

38
00:02:39,459 --> 00:02:44,397
How he had come to be wandering
all that time.

39
00:02:57,210 --> 00:03:02,512
"It began" he said,
"some time before."

40
00:03:02,582 --> 00:03:06,109
Days, weeks, months, years ever.

41
00:03:06,186 --> 00:03:09,178
He couldn't tell anymore.

42
00:03:09,255 --> 00:03:13,283
It began when "she"
came down to earth.

43
00:03:13,359 --> 00:03:16,852
She... from Epsilon.

44
00:03:54,267 --> 00:03:56,998
He said that she hadn't known.

45
00:03:57,070 --> 00:04:01,632
Didn't know where she was...

46
00:04:01,708 --> 00:04:05,576
or even how she came
to be there.

47
00:04:08,314 --> 00:04:10,749
Everything was strange to her.

48
00:04:15,855 --> 00:04:18,722
The smells.

49
00:04:18,791 --> 00:04:21,192
The terrain.

50
00:04:21,261 --> 00:04:25,528
<i>The colors.</i>

51
00:04:25,598 --> 00:04:30,058
The light.

52
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:45,077
She was abandoned
in a place that was at once hostile...

53
00:04:45,151 --> 00:04:47,677
and majestic.

54
00:04:47,754 --> 00:04:52,692
Ow Drumbeats ♪

55
00:04:56,162 --> 00:04:59,359
♪

56
00:05:01,634 --> 00:05:04,069
Everything was strange to her.

57
00:05:06,272 --> 00:05:08,707
The way time passed,

58
00:05:11,544 --> 00:05:16,482
The movement of the sun
and the clouds.

59
00:05:16,549 --> 00:05:20,281
The moon and
what the stars looked like.

60
00:05:20,353 --> 00:05:23,516
♪

61
00:05:29,729 --> 00:05:33,188
Nothing made sense.

62
00:05:33,266 --> 00:05:37,464
What was this place
she had come to?

63
00:05:37,537 --> 00:05:42,441
Is this a true story, Grandma,
or are you just making it up?

64
00:05:42,508 --> 00:05:45,808
I have only his word for it.

65
00:05:45,878 --> 00:05:49,280
But I believed him.

66
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:52,512
- I believed him.
- The wandering man?

67
00:05:52,585 --> 00:05:54,952
The wandering man.

68
00:06:02,362 --> 00:06:07,300
"Days were like
minutes to her," he said.

69
00:06:09,535 --> 00:06:12,630
Time meant nothing.

70
00:06:19,645 --> 00:06:24,515
For days and minutes,
she looked around,

71
00:06:24,584 --> 00:06:29,522
Looked everywhere
without moving anywhere.

72
00:06:36,329 --> 00:06:39,993
<i>Still she couldn't find
where she was.</i>

73
00:06:40,066 --> 00:06:45,004
Still she didn't know
what had happened to her.

74
00:06:48,007 --> 00:06:50,977
Why didn't she just
go back to Epsilon?

75
00:06:51,043 --> 00:06:54,707
It wasn't so easy, child,

76
00:06:54,781 --> 00:06:58,581
She longed to go back
to Epsilon,

77
00:06:58,651 --> 00:07:02,918
but she had no way of knowing
where Epsilon was...

78
00:07:02,989 --> 00:07:05,924
or how to get back there.

79
00:07:19,505 --> 00:07:21,439
She was lost.

80
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:26,644
Not just lost in a place,

81
00:07:26,712 --> 00:07:30,478
but lost in the whole universe.

82
00:07:30,550 --> 00:07:32,848
Ow Drumbeats ♪

83
00:07:44,063 --> 00:07:46,498
She stood.

84
00:07:48,968 --> 00:07:53,929
She stood for another day
and another minute...

85
00:07:56,175 --> 00:07:58,803
in the same place,

86
00:08:01,180 --> 00:08:04,377
but somewhere else, looking.

87
00:08:13,626 --> 00:08:18,063
Looking everywhere and anywhere.

88
00:08:18,130 --> 00:08:20,064
Under the alien sun.

89
00:08:24,871 --> 00:08:27,306
Under the foreign stars.

90
00:08:35,982 --> 00:08:40,647
Until, at last, she came back
to the place where she'd landed...

91
00:08:40,720 --> 00:08:42,654
and saw his fire,

92
00:08:44,090 --> 00:08:46,457
and saw him.

93
00:08:46,526 --> 00:08:48,460
The wandering man?

94
00:08:51,898 --> 00:08:57,667
He was an ordinary man
camped in the desert.

95
00:08:58,905 --> 00:09:02,603
But he was outside
that strange time of hers.

96
00:09:06,178 --> 00:09:09,079
To her he looked like...

97
00:09:09,148 --> 00:09:11,742
like some sort of insect.

98
00:09:11,817 --> 00:09:14,047
Like a human insect.

99
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:16,953
Grandma, this is scary.

100
00:09:17,023 --> 00:09:20,721
Not really scary.
More strange than scary.

101
00:09:20,793 --> 00:09:25,390
- What happened then?
- She just changed time.

102
00:09:28,167 --> 00:09:32,570
[ Crickets Chirping Slowly ♪

103
00:09:33,806 --> 00:09:37,800
And walked
right into his campsite.

104
00:09:37,877 --> 00:09:40,744
Um, good day.

105
00:09:40,813 --> 00:09:45,774
- Where are we?
- Um, here... in the bush.

106
00:09:45,851 --> 00:09:48,252
Um, you haven't got anything...

107
00:09:48,321 --> 00:09:52,918
- This is not Epsilon, is it?
- N-No, I don't think it is.

108
00:09:52,992 --> 00:09:55,893
- Here. You better put something on.
- Where?

109
00:09:55,962 --> 00:09:59,193
I think we're somewhere
on Dumbulga Station.

110
00:09:59,265 --> 00:10:01,632
I don't know it.

111
00:10:01,701 --> 00:10:06,298
Which star system is that?

112
00:10:06,372 --> 00:10:11,640
Um, are you all right?
Here, put this on.

113
00:10:11,711 --> 00:10:14,908
I'll be fine
once I know where I am.

114
00:10:14,981 --> 00:10:17,473
I don't recognize the stars.

115
00:10:17,550 --> 00:10:20,679
Could you please tell me
which star system we're in?

116
00:10:20,753 --> 00:10:23,779
I'm a surveyor,
not an astronomer.

117
00:10:23,856 --> 00:10:27,486
Please, put this on. I'm having
trouble following the conversation.

118
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:32,430
- How's that going to help?
- Just do it, will ya?

119
00:10:32,498 --> 00:10:37,698
There's no logical connection, but if
it will help you talk sense, okay.

120
00:10:42,541 --> 00:10:45,567
- Coordinates.
- Uh, the buttons too.

121
00:10:45,645 --> 00:10:48,342
I don't know what
you're talking about.

122
00:10:48,414 --> 00:10:52,612
- Where did you come from?
- I'm from Epsilon.

123
00:10:52,685 --> 00:10:54,949
Where's Epsilon?

124
00:10:55,021 --> 00:10:58,514
That's what
I'm trying to find out.

125
00:10:58,591 --> 00:11:02,425
This doesn't seem
to be helping you at all.

126
00:11:02,495 --> 00:11:05,362
Let's start again.

127
00:11:05,431 --> 00:11:10,460
Where... are... we?

128
00:11:11,704 --> 00:11:16,505
Which... star... system?

129
00:11:20,346 --> 00:11:24,806
Dum... bul... ga...

130
00:11:24,884 --> 00:11:27,785
Station, here on Earth.

131
00:11:31,257 --> 00:11:35,319
- Did you say "Earth"?
- Yes.

132
00:11:35,394 --> 00:11:39,524
You mean...
the planet Earth?

133
00:11:39,598 --> 00:11:44,331
I'll put the kettle on.
We'll have a nice cup of tea.

134
00:11:44,403 --> 00:11:46,735
You idiots.

135
00:11:46,806 --> 00:11:51,368
You damn, stupid idiots.
How could you?

136
00:11:51,444 --> 00:11:55,039
How could you make
such a stupid mistake?

137
00:11:55,114 --> 00:11:58,516
- This somebody's idea of a joke?
- Hey! Hey!

138
00:11:58,584 --> 00:12:01,713
Don't you come near me,
you destroyer!

139
00:12:01,787 --> 00:12:04,347
You're mad! You're mad!

140
00:12:04,423 --> 00:12:07,358
Making your filth
and living in it.

141
00:12:07,426 --> 00:12:10,623
And wrecking and breeding,
and wasting...

142
00:12:10,696 --> 00:12:13,222
and devouring everything!

143
00:12:13,299 --> 00:12:19,033
Don't you come near me,
you, you... poison!

144
00:12:19,105 --> 00:12:22,632
Get me off this vile planet!

145
00:12:25,077 --> 00:12:30,072
Poor man. I think
he was more confused than she.

146
00:12:30,149 --> 00:12:35,679
He decided that she must've been
mentally disturbed somehow.

147
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:39,521
And he was very careful
what he said after that.

148
00:12:39,992 --> 00:12:43,257
Lovely design, aren't they?

149
00:12:43,329 --> 00:12:48,130
Eggs, I mean.
Nice, rounded shape.

150
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:50,134
Such a convenient size.

151
00:13:03,249 --> 00:13:06,184
You're not gonna
start that again?

152
00:13:14,226 --> 00:13:17,662
Nature's own
crafty little package.

153
00:13:21,667 --> 00:13:24,136
Did your car break down?

154
00:13:31,277 --> 00:13:34,713
Tastes bloody good.
Nutritious too.

155
00:13:37,683 --> 00:13:41,642
I don't go much for all
those cholesterol theories myself.

156
00:13:45,024 --> 00:13:47,857
Run out of petrol maybe?

157
00:13:47,927 --> 00:13:51,795
Well, it happens, you know.

158
00:13:51,864 --> 00:13:54,424
You've gotta
cook 'em right though.

159
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:57,595
Consistency of the yolk's
the key.

160
00:14:07,313 --> 00:14:10,442
Did you run away from someone?

161
00:14:12,885 --> 00:14:18,346
It's understandable, the things they do
to people in some of those places.

162
00:14:30,603 --> 00:14:34,164
Soft...
but not too runny.

163
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:37,471
And the white has to be firm.

164
00:14:50,990 --> 00:14:56,087
I've never heard of anyone
coming down out of the stars before.

165
00:14:58,397 --> 00:15:01,196
How do you like yours?
Hey!

166
00:15:04,136 --> 00:15:06,730
Same as mine?

167
00:15:08,774 --> 00:15:12,506
- You're gonna have to help me get off.
- Me? Off where?

168
00:15:12,578 --> 00:15:15,070
Here. Off here.
Off Earth.

169
00:15:15,147 --> 00:15:20,278
- Oh, you mean this vile planet?
- Yes.

170
00:15:20,352 --> 00:15:22,377
Looks okay to me.

171
00:15:22,454 --> 00:15:25,480
- That's because you're like a frog.
- Oh, I see.

172
00:15:25,557 --> 00:15:29,357
You don't see at all.
Have you ever cooked a live frog?

173
00:15:29,428 --> 00:15:32,090
Why would I want to do that?

174
00:15:32,164 --> 00:15:34,599
You might learn something.

175
00:15:42,274 --> 00:15:45,733
When you drop a frog
into a pot of boiling water,

176
00:15:45,811 --> 00:15:49,213
it'll jump straight back out
to save itself.

177
00:15:49,281 --> 00:15:54,117
But if you put a frog into a pot
of cold water and heat it slowly,

178
00:15:54,186 --> 00:15:59,352
it'll swim around quite happily
until the water gets too hot...

179
00:15:59,425 --> 00:16:01,757
and kills it.

180
00:16:03,929 --> 00:16:07,160
So?

181
00:16:07,232 --> 00:16:13,103
Are you representative of the level of
intelligence here, or are you particularly stupid?

182
00:16:13,172 --> 00:16:16,164
About average, Id say.

183
00:16:16,241 --> 00:16:19,404
This place is worse
than I thought.

184
00:16:23,716 --> 00:16:27,846
What happens to the second frog
is what's happening to you here...

185
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:30,514
right this minute.

186
00:16:30,589 --> 00:16:34,526
And I want to get off
before the water boils.

187
00:16:38,797 --> 00:16:41,596
Your eggs are burning.

188
00:16:41,667 --> 00:16:45,228
He had the beginnings
of a real problem on his hands.

189
00:16:45,304 --> 00:16:47,238
Eggs!

190
00:16:47,439 --> 00:16:52,707
He wanted nothing more
than to be rid of her,

191
00:16:52,778 --> 00:16:56,146
but she showed
no signs of going.

192
00:16:57,983 --> 00:17:02,181
Did you some more eggs.
They're perfect.

193
00:17:08,994 --> 00:17:13,431
And he couldn't
find it within himself to cast her out.

194
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:20,063
He began to consider what
his course of action should be.

195
00:17:22,474 --> 00:17:25,466
He needn't have.

196
00:17:25,544 --> 00:17:30,243
Events soon spiraled
out of his control.

197
00:17:30,315 --> 00:17:33,478
What's this?

198
00:17:33,552 --> 00:17:36,578
Bacon.

199
00:17:36,655 --> 00:17:39,784
- You mean dead pig.
- It's bacon.

200
00:17:41,560 --> 00:17:46,259
Why don't you call it "dead pig"
if you know that's what it is?

201
00:17:48,734 --> 00:17:52,261
Why don't you let me enjoy
my breakfast?

202
00:18:12,291 --> 00:18:14,726
How can you do it?

203
00:18:15,861 --> 00:18:17,795
Do what?

204
00:18:17,863 --> 00:18:20,662
Eat dead pig.

205
00:18:20,732 --> 00:18:22,757
It's wasteful of resources.

206
00:18:22,835 --> 00:18:25,600
It's cruel in the extreme,
and is symptomatic...

207
00:18:25,671 --> 00:18:30,074
- of an immature and egocentric society.
- It's a lot of big words.

208
00:18:30,142 --> 00:18:32,839
Oh.

209
00:18:34,646 --> 00:18:38,583
In small words,
it means you're a barbarian.

210
00:18:44,423 --> 00:18:48,917
I'm going. I'll take you to
the nearest town, about two hours away.

211
00:18:48,994 --> 00:18:53,056
Or into the city if you're going
that far. That's the best I can do.

212
00:18:53,132 --> 00:18:56,796
Not bad for a frog. Don't know
what we'll do about the clothes.

213
00:18:56,869 --> 00:19:00,100
We're not going into the city. There are
too many people. They'll never find me.

214
00:19:00,172 --> 00:19:05,440
Fine by me. I'm going to the city,
you can do what you like.

215
00:19:05,511 --> 00:19:07,502
Are you going in this?

216
00:19:07,579 --> 00:19:11,516
No, there's a helicopter
arriving in five minutes.

217
00:19:12,985 --> 00:19:15,955
These things are
the most primitive,

218
00:19:16,021 --> 00:19:19,980
dirty and greedy things
ever invented.

219
00:19:20,058 --> 00:19:24,723
I'm not going to be an accessory
to the murder of this planet...

220
00:19:24,796 --> 00:19:26,890
Oy! Oy!

221
00:19:26,965 --> 00:19:30,663
Get out of it!
You're mad, you know that?

222
00:19:30,736 --> 00:19:34,832
Completely mad!
We're miles from anywhere. Miles!

223
00:19:34,907 --> 00:19:37,535
Come crashing into my campsite,
disturb my peace.

224
00:19:37,609 --> 00:19:43,048
I lend you my clothes, you won't
eat my eggs and now you wreck my truck!

225
00:19:50,222 --> 00:19:53,248
Sorry.

226
00:19:56,094 --> 00:19:58,791
Sorry.

227
00:19:58,864 --> 00:20:02,823
Sorry for losing my temper like that.

228
00:20:02,901 --> 00:20:06,667
I didn't mean to say you're mad.

229
00:20:06,738 --> 00:20:11,767
It's just, I only finished
paying it off last month.

230
00:20:11,843 --> 00:20:15,643
That's all right. It's good
to give in to your feelings.

231
00:20:17,082 --> 00:20:21,076
-You really like this thing, don't you?
Yes.

232
00:20:21,153 --> 00:20:25,351
I've put a lot of work into it.
Well, the mechanics.

233
00:20:25,424 --> 00:20:27,358
The body's next.

234
00:20:33,232 --> 00:20:36,395
And you really like it here,
don't you?

235
00:20:36,468 --> 00:20:39,369
Yeah, it's one
of my favorite places.

236
00:20:39,438 --> 00:20:43,033
Look, I'm sorry
for pushing you like that.

237
00:20:43,108 --> 00:20:45,839
I want to show you something.

238
00:20:45,911 --> 00:20:48,312
Look over there.

239
00:21:12,504 --> 00:21:15,474
See the contradiction?

240
00:21:21,713 --> 00:21:25,047
That was a pretty good trick.

241
00:21:25,117 --> 00:21:29,054
- How'd you do it?
- I'm from Epsilon.

242
00:21:30,856 --> 00:21:36,124
Mmm. Sorry
I ever doubted it.

243
00:21:36,194 --> 00:21:41,758
Are we actually here,
or do I just think we're here?

244
00:21:41,833 --> 00:21:44,131
We're actually here.

245
00:21:44,202 --> 00:21:47,172
<i>He was finally
compelled to admit to himself...</i>

246
00:21:47,239 --> 00:21:49,936
that she might, after all,

247
00:21:50,008 --> 00:21:53,876
be who she'd said she was.

248
00:21:53,945 --> 00:21:55,879
Useful way to travel.

249
00:21:55,947 --> 00:22:00,009
It was not the only surprise
she had for him.

250
00:22:16,968 --> 00:22:20,495
I'm finding this
a bit hard to grasp.

251
00:22:21,473 --> 00:22:24,670
- Lovely paradox, isn't it?
- What?

252
00:22:24,743 --> 00:22:28,839
The more I slow you down,
the faster things seem to go.

253
00:22:28,914 --> 00:22:33,010
You live your lives
very quickly.

254
00:22:44,763 --> 00:22:49,098
Afterwards he was to say
that in these early moments with her...

255
00:22:49,167 --> 00:22:51,829
he'd felt curiously composed,

256
00:22:51,903 --> 00:22:54,338
as if discovering
this other world...

257
00:22:54,406 --> 00:22:59,469
was no different from visiting
a new place or another country.

258
00:23:02,881 --> 00:23:07,045
I think the reality was somehow
a little different.

259
00:23:07,119 --> 00:23:09,645
From his memory of it.

260
00:23:09,721 --> 00:23:11,655
I'm getting dizzy!

261
00:23:11,723 --> 00:23:16,354
These concepts are obviously too much
for your incredibly limited intellect.

262
00:23:16,428 --> 00:23:20,729
I'm not talking about that. I'm getting
dizzy with what's happening to me.

263
00:23:20,799 --> 00:23:24,633
- You don't get the point, do you?
- I get the point, all right.

264
00:23:24,703 --> 00:23:29,140
- It's just my brain's a bit slow catching up.
- How very perceptive of you.

265
00:23:29,207 --> 00:23:31,232
We're in one place one second,

266
00:23:31,309 --> 00:23:34,574
then we're somewhere completely
different in the same second.

267
00:23:34,646 --> 00:23:38,514
Then everything speeds up, and it
gets dark and we're somewhere else,

268
00:23:38,583 --> 00:23:41,746
and I barely know
who I am anymore!

269
00:23:41,820 --> 00:23:44,380
No need to shout.

270
00:23:49,661 --> 00:23:52,995
- Where are we?
- Still here.

271
00:23:53,064 --> 00:23:56,728
- Still where?
- Still on Earth.

272
00:23:58,470 --> 00:24:02,668
The stars!
The stars are moving.

273
00:24:02,741 --> 00:24:05,142
The stars are not moving.

274
00:24:05,210 --> 00:24:08,510
<i>That's your Earth turning.</i>

275
00:24:08,580 --> 00:24:10,514
Oh.

276
00:24:16,188 --> 00:24:18,122
I knew that.

277
00:24:21,726 --> 00:24:23,717
Look.

278
00:24:34,005 --> 00:24:36,702
[ Birds Chirping ♪

279
00:24:36,775 --> 00:24:41,679
She'd returned him
to where he'd started.

280
00:24:44,716 --> 00:24:48,710
But he didn't know
when anymore, or how.

281
00:24:52,491 --> 00:24:56,724
<i>Or even if
he was really there...</i>

282
00:24:56,795 --> 00:25:00,163
or somewhere strange
in his mind.

283
00:25:00,232 --> 00:25:02,098
Where's my truck gone?

284
00:25:02,167 --> 00:25:05,102
You just haven't arrived yet.

285
00:25:10,175 --> 00:25:14,476
How am I ever going to arrive
if my truck's broken?

286
00:25:14,546 --> 00:25:18,881
I thought it would be obvious
to you that I haven't broken it yet.

287
00:25:23,154 --> 00:25:25,350
Not that obvious.

288
00:25:25,423 --> 00:25:28,120
We'd better get back
into the present.

289
00:25:28,193 --> 00:25:31,424
If I'm here before I got here,
they won't be looking for me yet.

290
00:25:31,496 --> 00:25:35,956
And when later on they do look,
I won't be here for them to find me.

291
00:25:36,034 --> 00:25:38,002
Yeah.

292
00:25:39,204 --> 00:25:42,037
Yeah?

293
00:25:45,277 --> 00:25:50,374
And then he began to think
about what was really happening to him.

294
00:25:50,448 --> 00:25:52,439
This is incredible!

295
00:25:54,553 --> 00:25:59,115
And what it could mean to Aim
if he wasn't imagining it.

296
00:26:02,327 --> 00:26:04,955
He had an idea, you see.

297
00:26:07,432 --> 00:26:10,265
Is it possible
for me to do this?

298
00:26:10,335 --> 00:26:13,134
- Do what?
- You know.

299
00:26:13,204 --> 00:26:17,766
Just sort of zap around from place
to place wherever I think of.

300
00:26:17,842 --> 00:26:21,870
I doubt if you have the mental capacity
to learn to do it by yourself.

301
00:26:21,947 --> 00:26:25,349
I thought it would be obvious to you that
I didn't mean I'd be doing it by myself,

302
00:26:25,417 --> 00:26:27,943
but is it possible?

303
00:26:28,019 --> 00:26:32,320
- Why would you want to?
- I've had this idea.

304
00:26:32,390 --> 00:26:34,825
I guess, as long
as you're with me.

305
00:26:34,893 --> 00:26:38,557
Okay.
Okay, I'll try it.

306
00:26:38,630 --> 00:26:42,589
Bear with me.
It'll be worth it.

307
00:26:43,668 --> 00:26:46,228
- Don't look.
- No.

308
00:26:55,046 --> 00:26:58,573
Where are we?
We should be somewhere else.

309
00:26:58,650 --> 00:27:00,584
You mean there?

310
00:27:00,652 --> 00:27:03,986
Huh! Got us close,
didn't I?

311
00:27:04,055 --> 00:27:07,958
Not bad for a first time.
Now I'll see if I can get us closer.

312
00:27:16,901 --> 00:27:20,929
- Nothing happened.
- That's 'cause I don't want to go there.

313
00:27:21,006 --> 00:27:24,271
Are you kidding?
That's Las Vegas!

314
00:27:24,342 --> 00:27:28,210
I've always wanted to go to Las Vegas.
I've got a system.

315
00:27:28,279 --> 00:27:30,270
- Have you?
- Mm-hmm.

316
00:27:30,348 --> 00:27:33,318
Well, off you go then.

317
00:27:36,321 --> 00:27:38,255
Bye.

318
00:27:40,825 --> 00:27:43,624
Have fun.

319
00:27:45,163 --> 00:27:48,064
<i>How do I get back to normal?</i>

320
00:27:50,602 --> 00:27:53,037
Normal time, I mean.

321
00:27:53,104 --> 00:27:56,074
Use your brains.

322
00:27:56,141 --> 00:27:58,075
Right.

323
00:27:58,143 --> 00:28:00,840
Good luck!

324
00:28:04,482 --> 00:28:07,213
He admitted later
that his first thoughts had been...

325
00:28:07,285 --> 00:28:10,721
how he, himself,
could benefit from this...

326
00:28:10,789 --> 00:28:13,190
unusual liaison.

327
00:28:21,232 --> 00:28:26,227
<i>A night in the most acquisitive place
on Earth, however,</i>

328
00:28:26,304 --> 00:28:31,401
was to be enough
to cure him of such notions.

329
00:28:36,481 --> 00:28:41,578
For a moment he considered
finding his own way home.

330
00:28:43,888 --> 00:28:48,587
But the lure of possibility
was too strong,

331
00:28:48,660 --> 00:28:51,630
and he found himself
returning to her.

332
00:29:00,305 --> 00:29:03,331
- Sorry I kept you waiting so long.
- It was nothing, really.

333
00:29:03,408 --> 00:29:06,002
Whoo-hoo!
Did I have a time of it!

334
00:29:06,077 --> 00:29:11,140
- I was on a roll. It was great.
- Did your system work?

335
00:29:11,216 --> 00:29:15,676
Well, it works.
Just didn't work this time.

336
00:29:15,754 --> 00:29:17,688
Fun, eh?

337
00:29:18,857 --> 00:29:21,656
Life is one long search for fun.

338
00:29:21,726 --> 00:29:24,286
Some people never find it.

339
00:29:24,362 --> 00:29:26,888
Don't knock it
when somebody does.

340
00:29:26,965 --> 00:29:31,027
- Oh. So you do actually think!
- Yeah.

341
00:29:31,102 --> 00:29:33,036
About life, I mean.

342
00:29:33,104 --> 00:29:36,096
I just don't dwell on it,
that's all.

343
00:29:36,174 --> 00:29:40,304
I got your point.
The trucks, the traffic jam.

344
00:29:40,378 --> 00:29:43,473
It's just...
there's no easy answers.

345
00:29:46,117 --> 00:29:48,745
He was right.

346
00:29:48,820 --> 00:29:51,949
There are no easy answers.

347
00:29:55,693 --> 00:30:00,187
But she was determined to force him
to think about the questions.

348
00:30:00,265 --> 00:30:02,324
What do you see down there?

349
00:30:02,400 --> 00:30:05,836
A city covered with smog.

350
00:30:05,904 --> 00:30:10,466
Ten million frogs
slowly boiling to death.

351
00:30:10,542 --> 00:30:14,206
It is, for me,

352
00:30:14,279 --> 00:30:19,342
unimaginable that you people
choose to live like this.

353
00:30:21,352 --> 00:30:24,617
There are ten million people
down there.

354
00:30:24,689 --> 00:30:29,525
They cough, they complain,
their children get sick.

355
00:30:33,298 --> 00:30:35,596
Here on Earth
you have an expression.

356
00:30:35,667 --> 00:30:40,161
"Sticking your head in the sand."
The ostrich mentality,

357
00:30:40,238 --> 00:30:44,800
because that's what ostriches do
to make problems go away.

358
00:30:44,876 --> 00:30:50,679
In the rest of the universe, we have an
expression that means almost the same thing.

359
00:30:50,748 --> 00:30:55,310
It is,
"To breathe the foul air."

360
00:30:55,386 --> 00:30:59,880
If we say someone
is breathing the foul air,

361
00:30:59,958 --> 00:31:03,019
we mean they have
the Earth mentality.

362
00:31:03,094 --> 00:31:08,533
It is about the worst insult
you can level at someone...

363
00:31:08,600 --> 00:31:12,059
<i>because having the Earth mentality
is the one thing...</i>

364
00:31:12,136 --> 00:31:17,597
that is truly unforgivable
in the rest of the universe.

365
00:31:23,648 --> 00:31:26,618
Can we go
somewhere else, please?

366
00:31:26,684 --> 00:31:31,588
Somewhere where
I can see some stars.

367
00:31:51,242 --> 00:31:53,176
He knew by this time...

368
00:31:53,244 --> 00:31:58,182
that nothing in his life
would ever be the same again.

369
00:32:13,631 --> 00:32:16,100
I feel better now.

370
00:32:17,835 --> 00:32:22,068
What did you mean,
the rest of the universe?

371
00:32:22,140 --> 00:32:27,442
- You know what is meant by "intelligent life-forms"?
- Of course I do.

372
00:32:27,512 --> 00:32:30,812
- Well, you're not one of them.
- I'm not?

373
00:32:30,882 --> 00:32:33,214
Not just you.

374
00:32:33,284 --> 00:32:37,517
The human race is not considered in universal
terms to be an intelligent life-form.

375
00:32:37,588 --> 00:32:40,649
- I suppose you lot are?
- Yes, of course.

376
00:32:43,194 --> 00:32:45,128
One of many.

377
00:33:09,554 --> 00:33:12,546
She began to talk with him.

378
00:33:12,623 --> 00:33:16,253
Talk of how the intelligent life-forms
of the universe...

379
00:33:16,327 --> 00:33:20,764
<i>had concluded that Earth
was beyond help.</i>

380
00:33:23,368 --> 00:33:29,000
Earth had proved itself to be
the most irrational of all known places,

381
00:33:29,073 --> 00:33:34,773
the least willing to listen
to the most obvious.

382
00:33:34,846 --> 00:33:37,508
He denied it, of course.

383
00:33:37,582 --> 00:33:42,782
<i>But when she told him that Earth
had now been left to destroy itself...</i>

384
00:33:42,854 --> 00:33:45,551
by its own devices,

385
00:33:45,623 --> 00:33:48,285
he fell silent.

386
00:33:49,727 --> 00:33:55,222
"Why, then, had she come here?"
he eventually asked,

387
00:33:55,299 --> 00:33:59,463
And she didn't know.
She couldn't answer him.

388
00:33:59,537 --> 00:34:03,405
She thought
it must've been a mistake,

389
00:34:03,474 --> 00:34:07,672
and she hoped she would
soon be discovered and taken off.

390
00:34:09,814 --> 00:34:13,682
Knowing at least some of what she said
to have been true,

391
00:34:13,751 --> 00:34:16,311
it had made him laugh.

392
00:34:16,387 --> 00:34:21,348
Laugh out loud
at the bizarre turn int £175 fife.

393
00:34:21,426 --> 00:34:25,192
I'm glad you're able
to take it in such good humor.

394
00:34:25,263 --> 00:34:30,758
You earthlings have always been
exceptionally good at denying reality.

395
00:34:30,835 --> 00:34:33,270
I think we ought to have
a relationship.

396
00:34:33,337 --> 00:34:35,806
Would you mind?

397
00:34:35,873 --> 00:34:39,070
Hell.
I beg your pardon?

398
00:34:39,143 --> 00:34:41,737
I feel the need
to have a relationship.

399
00:34:41,813 --> 00:34:45,443
We're together anyway, so it makes
perfect sense to be having a relationship.

400
00:34:45,516 --> 00:34:48,816
- We hardly know each other.
- It's quite easy, really.

401
00:34:48,886 --> 00:34:52,516
We'll treat each other with respect
and kindness, and have a relationship.

402
00:34:52,590 --> 00:34:54,922
- Just like that, eh?
- Is that so hard?

403
00:34:54,992 --> 00:34:58,895
No, no.
Suits me fine.

404
00:34:58,963 --> 00:35:01,364
Some simple rules
need to be followed.

405
00:35:01,432 --> 00:35:05,835
Say what you mean,
mean what you say.

406
00:35:05,903 --> 00:35:10,465
Don't get offended by anything I say or do,
no matter how hard that might be for you...

407
00:35:10,541 --> 00:35:14,478
until after we've agreed
to terminate the relationship.

408
00:35:14,545 --> 00:35:17,242
Don't bottle up your feelings,

409
00:35:17,315 --> 00:35:19,647
agree to disagree,

410
00:35:19,717 --> 00:35:23,312
respect the other's
point of view.

411
00:35:23,387 --> 00:35:26,880
That's the one that's going to be
hardest for me. Okay?

412
00:35:26,958 --> 00:35:29,723
- Sounds easy enough.
- Good.

413
00:35:29,794 --> 00:35:32,661
That's decided then.

414
00:35:35,366 --> 00:35:37,300
Hmm.

415
00:35:39,804 --> 00:35:42,637
If we're having a relationship,

416
00:35:42,707 --> 00:35:46,666
I think you should
tuck your shirt in.

417
00:35:46,744 --> 00:35:50,271
If that's what you'd like...
darling.

418
00:35:50,348 --> 00:35:53,215
This is all going
a bit fast for me.

419
00:35:53,284 --> 00:35:57,482
Would you mind not using that word until
our relationship's a bit better established?

420
00:35:57,555 --> 00:36:00,217
- Sure.
- Thanks.

421
00:36:00,291 --> 00:36:04,728
- Let's go.
- That's how it started.

422
00:36:04,795 --> 00:36:08,129
But progress did not prove
to be in fine with his expectations.

423
00:36:08,332 --> 00:36:10,323
Where are we now?

424
00:36:10,401 --> 00:36:12,802
Still the same place.

425
00:36:14,872 --> 00:36:18,502
We're obviously
in a different place.

426
00:36:18,576 --> 00:36:21,546
I can't see the difference.

427
00:36:23,181 --> 00:36:28,176
You Epsilonians certainly have
a different way of looking at things.

428
00:36:28,252 --> 00:36:31,187
It's not us, it's you that are
out of step.

429
00:36:31,255 --> 00:36:34,589
With the rest of the universe?

430
00:36:34,659 --> 00:36:39,927
- Won't that affect the course of our relationship?
- No, it doesn't have to.

431
00:36:39,997 --> 00:36:42,796
- Could you lend me your belt?
- What's my belt got to do with it?

432
00:36:42,867 --> 00:36:46,064
You obviously
find me attractive.

433
00:36:46,137 --> 00:36:49,300
So in order to help this early part
of our relationship,

434
00:36:49,373 --> 00:36:55,107
Id like to put your belt around
my waist to accentuate my female shape.

435
00:36:55,179 --> 00:36:58,809
When you look at me,
which you do quite often,

436
00:36:58,883 --> 00:37:01,443
the signal to your brain
will be stronger,

437
00:37:01,519 --> 00:37:03,920
meaning your hormone release
will be greater.

438
00:37:03,988 --> 00:37:09,324
Hence, the relationship will improve...
from your point of view, anyway.

439
00:37:09,393 --> 00:37:13,193
I'm not sure
what's in it for me.

440
00:37:13,264 --> 00:37:15,198
Belt?

441
00:37:17,301 --> 00:37:19,235
What about feelings?

442
00:37:19,303 --> 00:37:23,137
I'm talking about much more powerful
things than feelings.

443
00:37:23,207 --> 00:37:25,301
I'm talking about hormones.

444
00:37:25,376 --> 00:37:28,311
I never think much
about them myself.

445
00:37:32,550 --> 00:37:36,487
Would you mind not doing that
without giving me some warning?

446
00:37:37,488 --> 00:37:39,820
It's very disorienting.

447
00:37:39,890 --> 00:37:43,258
You'll get used to it.

448
00:37:54,272 --> 00:37:58,675
I must say, it's about the last thing
I ever imagined.

449
00:37:58,743 --> 00:38:02,611
Having a relationship
with a being from Earth.

450
00:38:03,948 --> 00:38:06,610
Must be tough for your hormones,

451
00:38:06,684 --> 00:38:10,211
having to cope with
a pig-eating barbarian.

452
00:38:17,128 --> 00:38:20,758
- You're quaint.
- Just what I wanted to hear!

453
00:38:20,831 --> 00:38:25,132
I finally started a relationship,
and she thinks I'm quaint.

454
00:38:25,202 --> 00:38:27,637
How much warning do you want?

455
00:38:33,444 --> 00:38:36,072
Okay.

456
00:38:39,417 --> 00:38:43,411
- Where are we now?
- Same place.

457
00:38:43,487 --> 00:38:45,615
No, we're not.
We're somewhere different.

458
00:38:45,690 --> 00:38:48,921
We're in the same place,
still on Earth.

459
00:38:48,993 --> 00:38:53,021
Yes, but where on Earth?

460
00:38:53,097 --> 00:38:57,466
Do you think these trees
are trying to die by themselves?

461
00:38:57,535 --> 00:39:01,529
That they've just decided
to up and perish for no good reason?

462
00:39:03,541 --> 00:39:05,475
Well, do you?

463
00:39:05,543 --> 00:39:08,444
Or don't you think about it?

464
00:39:08,512 --> 00:39:11,709
Maybe they've got
a fungus or something.

465
00:39:11,782 --> 00:39:15,275
Maybe you've got
a fungus in your brain.

466
00:39:15,353 --> 00:39:18,220
He knew it wasn't a fungus.

467
00:39:18,289 --> 00:39:22,123
He knew why
those trees were dying.

468
00:39:22,193 --> 00:39:24,924
Like so many people
in those days,

469
00:39:24,995 --> 00:39:29,865
he didn't want to admit
that he knew.

470
00:39:29,934 --> 00:39:33,427
He would have condemned himself.
His whole way of life,

471
00:39:33,504 --> 00:39:36,872
his friends, his neighbors.

472
00:39:36,941 --> 00:39:42,846
Deep down he knew he'd killed those trees
as much as anyone had killed those trees...

473
00:39:42,913 --> 00:39:45,507
though he'd never
seen them before,

474
00:39:45,583 --> 00:39:49,281
never touched them.

475
00:39:49,353 --> 00:39:53,551
But even then, to her,
he couldn't admit it.

476
00:39:53,624 --> 00:39:57,254
So don't keep asking me,
"Where on Earth?"

477
00:39:57,328 --> 00:40:01,162
- It's all the same place.
- Right.

478
00:40:16,347 --> 00:40:18,782
What are you doing?

479
00:40:27,591 --> 00:40:29,923
What are you doing?

480
00:40:35,099 --> 00:40:38,194
What are you doing?

481
00:40:38,269 --> 00:40:41,295
- Looking for frogs.
- Oh.

482
00:40:48,946 --> 00:40:51,415
See any?

483
00:40:51,482 --> 00:40:53,746
Not yet.

484
00:40:59,890 --> 00:41:03,155
Why are you looking for frogs?

485
00:41:03,227 --> 00:41:08,324
- Frogs are a measure of the health of a place.
- Oh.

486
00:41:08,399 --> 00:41:11,835
I thought maybe you were gonna
boil one up for me.

487
00:41:11,902 --> 00:41:16,897
- Why would I want to do that?
- I might learn something.

488
00:41:28,519 --> 00:41:30,510
Hey!

489
00:41:30,588 --> 00:41:32,613
No frogs around here.

490
00:41:32,690 --> 00:41:35,022
That she might have
a sense of humor...

491
00:41:35,092 --> 00:41:37,959
was something he'd overlooked.

492
00:41:38,028 --> 00:41:43,194
She began to...
to affect Aim.

493
00:41:43,267 --> 00:41:46,532
He began, in his own way,

494
00:41:46,604 --> 00:41:49,164
to open up to her.

495
00:41:49,240 --> 00:41:53,768
My watch is behaving pretty strangely
with all this jumping around.

