01:01:51,455 --> 01:01:54,481
Your whole way of life
is one of extremes.

738
01:01:54,558 --> 01:01:56,890
You're wrong.

739
01:01:56,961 --> 01:02:00,090
I have a perfectly normal
way of life.

740
01:02:00,164 --> 01:02:05,159
It might be normal, but it doesn't
stop it from being extremely stupid.

741
01:02:09,940 --> 01:02:13,001
Id like to terminate
our relationship.

742
01:02:14,478 --> 01:02:17,379
Would that be agreeable to you?

743
01:02:19,383 --> 01:02:22,876
- Pity.
- Why?

744
01:02:25,422 --> 01:02:28,187
I was growing quite fond of you.

745
01:02:29,426 --> 01:02:32,521
That must've been nice for you.

746
01:02:33,797 --> 01:02:37,461
So, is the relationship
terminated?

747
01:02:37,534 --> 01:02:39,434
I guess it is.

748
01:02:39,503 --> 01:02:41,870
Good.

749
01:02:41,939 --> 01:02:45,136
I don't respect
your point of view.

750
01:02:45,209 --> 01:02:48,304
I can't agree to disagree.

751
01:02:48,379 --> 01:02:50,973
I get offended by the things
you say and do.

752
01:02:51,048 --> 01:02:55,315
And I don't think you say what you mean
or mean what you say any more than I do.

753
01:02:55,386 --> 01:02:58,879
And I like bottling up
some of my feelings.

754
01:02:58,956 --> 01:03:01,220
It causes a lot less trouble.

755
01:03:01,292 --> 01:03:03,954
That stuff might work
for you on Epsilon,

756
01:03:04,028 --> 01:03:06,793
but it doesn't work for me here.

757
01:03:11,101 --> 01:03:13,468
Fine.

758
01:03:15,973 --> 01:03:18,271
Well,

759
01:03:19,843 --> 01:03:23,643
<i>- what now?
- I'd better go.</i>

760
01:03:26,116 --> 01:03:28,050
Keep trying.

761
01:03:29,420 --> 01:03:32,287
- Will you be okay?
- I think so.

762
01:03:33,924 --> 01:03:37,519
It'll take me a while to figure out
how to fix that thing.

763
01:03:37,594 --> 01:03:41,030
Then I'll be on my way too.

764
01:03:44,535 --> 01:03:46,526
Okay, then.

765
01:03:46,603 --> 01:03:48,765
Good-bye.

766
01:03:48,839 --> 01:03:52,207
Good-bye.

767
01:03:56,714 --> 01:03:59,342
Your clothes,
I'm still wearing them.

768
01:03:59,416 --> 01:04:01,510
That's okay.
You can keep em.

769
01:04:01,585 --> 01:04:04,987
- Oh.
- You never know.

770
01:04:05,055 --> 01:04:08,423
You might meet someone else.
You'd need them then.

771
01:04:08,492 --> 01:04:13,191
Yes. You might be right.
Thank you.

772
01:04:13,263 --> 01:04:15,698
That's fine.

773
01:04:18,802 --> 01:04:22,170
It was a pleasure
to have met you.

774
01:04:26,009 --> 01:04:28,239
Good-bye then.

775
01:04:28,312 --> 01:04:30,371
Good-bye.

776
01:04:52,936 --> 01:04:55,462
"Twas funny in a way."

777
01:04:55,539 --> 01:04:59,203
Neither of them really wanted
to say good-bye,

778
01:05:00,778 --> 01:05:03,839
but both of them said it.

779
01:05:03,914 --> 01:05:08,579
And only then were they able
to give full consideration...

780
01:05:08,652 --> 01:05:10,916
to what had happened
between them.

781
01:05:27,638 --> 01:05:31,734
Aha! Incredibly
limited intellect, hey?

782
01:05:53,096 --> 01:05:55,963
I breathe the foul air.

783
01:06:06,643 --> 01:06:09,237
What else can I do?

784
01:06:10,380 --> 01:06:13,543
That's what makes me what [ am.

785
01:06:59,096 --> 01:07:02,555
Hi! I'm... back.

786
01:07:10,207 --> 01:07:14,906
For her,
nothing was ever too late.

787
01:07:18,015 --> 01:07:20,313
There's nothing
wrong with being quaint.

788
01:07:20,384 --> 01:07:23,363
- There is when I'm not trying to be.
- We're in a relationship.

789
01:07:23,387 --> 01:07:26,550
- She went back...
- We don't have to try to be anything.

790
01:07:26,623 --> 01:07:28,921
In time.

791
01:07:28,992 --> 01:07:32,326
I don't like to be considered quaint
when I'm in a relationship.

792
01:07:32,396 --> 01:07:35,093
But you are.

793
01:07:37,734 --> 01:07:40,499
- That always happens to me.
- What?

794
01:07:40,571 --> 01:07:45,236
Women tend to think I'm their
best friend, instead of, you know.

795
01:07:45,309 --> 01:07:49,303
I know what you're saying.
But tell me.

796
01:07:51,882 --> 01:07:55,011
- I had a girlfriend once.
- I know.

797
01:07:55,085 --> 01:07:57,486
Do you?
How?

798
01:07:57,554 --> 01:08:00,023
You...
talked about it before.

799
01:08:00,090 --> 01:08:03,321
Oh.
I don't remember.

800
01:08:03,393 --> 01:08:05,885
Anyway, we eventually broke up.

801
01:08:05,963 --> 01:08:10,901
A week later she came back
to visit me, see if I was okay.

802
01:08:10,968 --> 01:08:15,201
I sort of feel like I've
told you this story before.

803
01:08:15,272 --> 01:08:18,503
- Stop me if I have.
- No, goon.

804
01:08:18,575 --> 01:08:20,600
Okay.

805
01:08:21,678 --> 01:08:23,669
Where was I?

806
01:08:23,747 --> 01:08:28,776
You were saying she sat at the kitchen
table and told you she had a new boyfriend.

807
01:08:28,852 --> 01:08:31,947
Was I?
Oh.

808
01:08:33,557 --> 01:08:35,924
"Well, how long's
that been goin' on?" I said.

809
01:08:35,993 --> 01:08:39,258
- She said, "A week."
- That was quick. You'd only split up a week before.

810
01:08:39,329 --> 01:08:43,266
That's what I said!
How did you know?

811
01:08:43,333 --> 01:08:45,358
You just told me.

812
01:08:45,435 --> 01:08:48,530
Did I?
When?

813
01:08:48,605 --> 01:08:50,573
Just now.

814
01:08:53,110 --> 01:08:56,546
Are you sure I haven't told you
this story before?

815
01:08:56,613 --> 01:08:58,775
Not before.

816
01:08:58,849 --> 01:09:02,251
No, definitely not before.

817
01:09:02,319 --> 01:09:06,552
I keep getting these flashes
like I have.

818
01:09:11,695 --> 01:09:15,256
I get very confused when I try
and talk to you seriously.

819
01:09:15,332 --> 01:09:17,528
What was he like?

820
01:09:17,601 --> 01:09:19,831
- Who?
- The boyfriend,

821
01:09:21,171 --> 01:09:23,367
She said he wasn't
as nice as me.

822
01:09:23,440 --> 01:09:25,499
He wouldn't be.

823
01:09:26,576 --> 01:09:28,635
What do you mean?

824
01:09:28,712 --> 01:09:33,081
She's right.
He isn't as nice as you.

825
01:09:33,150 --> 01:09:35,482
- Do you know him?
- Of course I don't.

826
01:09:35,552 --> 01:09:40,319
- But you...
- I don't have to know him. I know you.

827
01:09:46,496 --> 01:09:48,760
I'm sorry.

828
01:09:48,832 --> 01:09:52,132
I don't think
you're all that quaint.

829
01:10:00,043 --> 01:10:05,038
1 suppose it must be nice
to be able to try one set of actions,

830
01:10:05,115 --> 01:10:10,246
and then, if things
don't quite work out,

831
01:10:10,320 --> 01:10:13,881
dispense with the outcome
of the consequences...

832
01:10:13,957 --> 01:10:17,985
and try another set of actions
for better results.

833
01:10:25,702 --> 01:10:28,728
But life on Farts
is not like that.

834
01:10:30,307 --> 01:10:34,710
We have to live with the consequences
of our actions.

835
01:10:38,849 --> 01:10:42,843
We are normally given
only one chance.

836
01:10:47,390 --> 01:10:51,554
The wandering man was given
a second chance,

837
01:10:51,628 --> 01:10:55,428
although he only knew
about that afterwards.

838
01:11:32,669 --> 01:11:36,765
He said it was
a most peculiar thing.

839
01:11:38,675 --> 01:11:44,478
He didn't then remember any
of the things that had happened to him,

840
01:11:45,916 --> 01:11:47,941
or hadn't happened,

841
01:11:48,018 --> 01:11:51,682
depending on how you look
at the past.

842
01:11:53,323 --> 01:11:56,953
I'm glad there's no time limit
on these things.

843
01:11:57,027 --> 01:11:59,155
So am I.

844
01:11:59,229 --> 01:12:01,994
Yet he still felt different.

845
01:12:02,065 --> 01:12:04,966
Thought differently,

846
01:12:05,035 --> 01:12:09,597
as if he'd been changed
by those events nevertheless.

847
01:12:24,487 --> 01:12:27,320
But for now, for him,

848
01:12:27,390 --> 01:12:30,655
there was only the present.

849
01:12:52,682 --> 01:12:55,310
If it had ended there,

850
01:12:55,385 --> 01:12:58,685
if somehow they'd lived
happily ever after,

851
01:12:58,755 --> 01:13:02,055
the outcome would have been
very different.

852
01:13:03,627 --> 01:13:06,824
The consequences
much more serious.

853
01:13:08,365 --> 01:13:12,097
But it hadn't quite ended yet.

854
01:13:38,962 --> 01:13:41,124
What's the matter?

855
01:13:41,197 --> 01:13:43,131
I'm sad.

856
01:13:43,199 --> 01:13:45,133
Don't be sad.

857
01:13:45,201 --> 01:13:47,829
Of course I'm sad.

858
01:13:55,478 --> 01:13:57,879
There's nothing to be sad about.

859
01:13:57,948 --> 01:14:01,714
I haven't finished
being sad yet.

860
01:14:02,886 --> 01:14:04,820
Oh.

861
01:14:21,705 --> 01:14:25,005
Now I've finished!

862
01:14:27,310 --> 01:14:30,610
What were you sad about?

863
01:14:30,680 --> 01:14:32,944
I was sad about...

864
01:14:33,016 --> 01:14:37,283
if I stay, I'll never
see Epsilon again.

865
01:14:37,354 --> 01:14:41,621
And if I go,
I'll never see you again.

866
01:14:41,691 --> 01:14:44,592
Whichever one
I thought about made me sad.

867
01:14:44,661 --> 01:14:46,595
Oh.

868
01:14:48,765 --> 01:14:53,066
Which one made you less sad?

869
01:14:56,673 --> 01:15:00,405
Will you show me your
comfortable little house now?

870
01:15:00,477 --> 01:15:02,969
The one with the spare room?

871
01:15:08,184 --> 01:15:12,746
It's my hormones.
You send them out of control.

872
01:15:12,822 --> 01:15:17,157
How did you know about my comfortable
little house and the spare room?

873
01:15:18,328 --> 01:15:22,788
It's a bit... complicated.

874
01:15:23,933 --> 01:15:28,495
You told me
in our previous past.

875
01:15:28,571 --> 01:15:31,404
We've got a previous past,
you and me?

876
01:15:31,474 --> 01:15:34,034
We ended up having an argument
and parting ways.

877
01:15:34,110 --> 01:15:39,378
So I came back and found you before we
had the argument and here we are.

878
01:15:39,449 --> 01:15:42,111
You have a fight
you wished you hadn't had,

879
01:15:42,185 --> 01:15:44,677
so you just go back
and you don't have it.

880
01:15:44,754 --> 01:15:46,813
Useful way to solve problems.

881
01:15:46,890 --> 01:15:49,985
- What was the argument about?
- You thought I was too extreme.

882
01:15:50,060 --> 01:15:53,428
I didn't!
I don't think you're extreme at all!

883
01:15:53,496 --> 01:15:57,023
- I'd never think that. Never!
- I am a bit at times.

884
01:15:57,100 --> 01:16:01,765
You're not extreme. You just feel
passionately about things.

885
01:16:03,106 --> 01:16:05,666
Things that are important.

886
01:16:05,742 --> 01:16:09,235
- Id chopped down your childhood tree.
- You what?

887
01:16:09,312 --> 01:16:12,748
I chopped down your tree, your favorite
tree, the one you used to talk to.

888
01:16:12,816 --> 01:16:14,784
You didn't!

889
01:16:14,851 --> 01:16:18,446
- You don't mind?
- You must've had good reason.

890
01:16:21,558 --> 01:16:25,392
I've been thinking about things.
You know?

891
01:16:25,462 --> 01:16:29,922
All the things you've been saying
about the Earth and so on.

892
01:16:29,999 --> 01:16:32,400
It all makes sense, but...

893
01:16:32,469 --> 01:16:35,700
you tend to get a bit
depressed about it at first.

894
01:16:35,772 --> 01:16:39,504
Thinking about how just one person
doesn't make any difference at all.

895
01:16:39,576 --> 01:16:42,102
What can I do anyway?
And all that.

896
01:16:43,813 --> 01:16:46,748
Then I thought about war.

897
01:16:50,220 --> 01:16:52,518
When there's a war on,

898
01:16:52,589 --> 01:16:56,116
when their country and their
way of life are threatened,

899
01:16:56,192 --> 01:17:00,322
people don't hesitate to change
their life completely, you know?

900
01:17:00,396 --> 01:17:02,455
To risk everything.

901
01:17:02,532 --> 01:17:06,196
Their job, their career,

902
01:17:06,269 --> 01:17:09,933
their life,
their family and friends.

903
01:17:10,006 --> 01:17:12,941
Dump the lot to join in the war.

904
01:17:13,009 --> 01:17:15,706
They're ready
to risk everything.

905
01:17:15,778 --> 01:17:19,112
Which is how it's got to be
to win the war.

906
01:17:20,416 --> 01:17:22,612
Doesn't make any sense, does it?

907
01:17:22,685 --> 01:17:25,279
This is a war.

908
01:17:25,355 --> 01:17:27,585
This is more than a war.

909
01:17:27,657 --> 01:17:30,251
But we muck around at the edges of it
like we're just playing.

910
01:17:30,326 --> 01:17:32,351
They've found me.

911
01:17:33,863 --> 01:17:37,128
What?

912
01:17:37,200 --> 01:17:39,931
They've found me.

913
01:17:40,003 --> 01:17:42,233
This is much more serious
than any war.

914
01:17:42,305 --> 01:17:45,138
We muck around at the edges of it
like we're just playing with it.

915
01:17:45,208 --> 01:17:48,769
Didn't you hear what I said?

916
01:17:48,845 --> 01:17:52,145
I heard what you said.

917
01:17:52,215 --> 01:17:55,617
Tell them to go away.

918
01:17:55,685 --> 01:17:57,744
I can't.

919
01:18:38,661 --> 01:18:42,120
What if they decide not to take me now?
We can't just keep doing this.

920
01:18:42,198 --> 01:18:46,328
You're right. We've got to think,
think clearly. Let me think.

921
01:18:46,402 --> 01:18:49,235
We've got to go back
to your truck.

922
01:18:49,305 --> 01:18:52,138
You know, in case
they do decide to take me,

923
01:18:52,208 --> 01:18:54,575
you're left stranded
in the middle of nowhere.

924
01:18:54,644 --> 01:18:58,911
- In the wrong time.
- Right.

925
01:18:58,982 --> 01:19:01,110
Let's go.

926
01:19:18,334 --> 01:19:21,702
Do you think if I just held on to you
the whole time that they couldn't...

927
01:19:21,771 --> 01:19:23,705
No.

928
01:19:23,773 --> 01:19:27,073
Didn't think so.

929
01:19:27,143 --> 01:19:29,669
But we could try.

930
01:19:39,889 --> 01:19:43,985
I wonder which one it is.

931
01:19:44,060 --> 01:19:46,256
I've decided it's that one...

932
01:19:46,329 --> 01:19:48,457
at the end of
that sort of trail.

933
01:19:48,531 --> 01:19:52,434
See it?
That's the one I'll be looking at.

934
01:19:52,502 --> 01:19:56,200
I could wave to you.

935
01:19:59,609 --> 01:20:03,136
I think I might become
an astronomer if you go.

936
01:20:03,212 --> 01:20:05,146
I wouldn't if were you.

937
01:20:05,214 --> 01:20:07,148
Why not?

938
01:20:07,216 --> 01:20:11,312
- You'll be out of a job in a few years' time.
- Why's that?

939
01:20:11,387 --> 01:20:14,584
This view is disappearing.

940
01:20:14,657 --> 01:20:18,685
You won't be able to see
any stars at all soon.

941
01:20:20,563 --> 01:20:24,500
- Better not become an astronomer then.
- No.

942
01:20:26,836 --> 01:20:29,806
I thought I might be able
to see you through the telescope.

943
01:20:34,344 --> 01:20:38,212
What's that silly expression?

944
01:20:38,281 --> 01:20:41,512
It's my "I'll be
a good father" look.

945
01:20:46,723 --> 01:20:51,752
If we weren't gonna bring children into
the world, there'd be no point saving it.

946
01:20:55,398 --> 01:21:00,097
There's no point bringing children
into the world until you've saved it.

947
01:21:04,107 --> 01:21:07,133
I think we might agree
to disagree there.

948
01:21:14,183 --> 01:21:18,381
We could go back
to when we first met...

949
01:21:18,454 --> 01:21:22,550
and just go "round and round
in time between then and now."

950
01:21:40,810 --> 01:21:44,075
I don't think they're coming.

951
01:21:50,119 --> 01:21:53,487
I don't feel them anymore.

952
01:21:57,326 --> 01:22:00,728
I feel you...

953
01:22:00,797 --> 01:22:03,596
and here,

954
01:22:05,601 --> 01:22:08,468
but not them.

955
01:22:13,810 --> 01:22:16,211
I feel...

956
01:22:16,279 --> 01:22:20,011
we might do
some things together.

957
01:22:21,551 --> 01:22:24,282
It's a nice feeling.

958
01:22:24,353 --> 01:22:27,789
Whoo-hoo!

959
01:22:48,911 --> 01:22:52,745
What was that?

960
01:22:52,815 --> 01:22:54,806
I call it my sharpie dance.

961
01:25:21,530 --> 01:25:25,091
It was some days
after this that I met him.

962
01:25:25,167 --> 01:25:30,970
Just that one time, for the few hours
it took him to tell his story.

963
01:25:33,009 --> 01:25:36,070
Then he slept briefly, woke,

964
01:25:36,145 --> 01:25:40,343
picked up his bag
and walked into the night...

965
01:25:40,416 --> 01:25:43,613
saying he had
some stories to tell,

966
01:25:43,686 --> 01:25:46,485
some stars to save.

967
01:26:05,074 --> 01:26:07,202
Did he disappear?

968
01:26:07,276 --> 01:26:12,840
No, he didn't disappear.

969
01:26:12,915 --> 01:26:18,786
A few years later,
I saw his photo in the newspaper.

970
01:26:18,854 --> 01:26:22,188
- I recognized him immediately.
- What's a newspaper?

971
01:26:22,258 --> 01:26:24,522
It's a thing they used to have
before they knew better.

972
01:26:24,593 --> 01:26:26,823
<i>- You're too young to know.
- I'm not too young.</i>

973
01:26:26,896 --> 01:26:31,265
In time, he began
to appear on television.

974
01:26:31,333 --> 01:26:35,497
To be written about,
talked about.

975
01:26:35,571 --> 01:26:40,668
Spreading his ideas
that he said weren't his ideas.

976
01:26:42,812 --> 01:26:46,976
At first, they considered him
to be a little mad himself.

977
01:26:48,384 --> 01:26:51,081
"Epsi-loon" they called Aim.

978
01:26:51,153 --> 01:26:53,178
Sounds like
they were madder than him.

979
01:26:53,255 --> 01:26:56,885
Not all of them.
There were others like him.

980
01:26:56,959 --> 01:27:01,362
Over the years, as the sense
of what he was saying just...

981
01:27:01,430 --> 01:27:04,491
just couldn't be argued against,

982
01:27:04,567 --> 01:27:07,730
they changed the way
they thought about him,

983
01:27:07,803 --> 01:27:11,205
and they gave him
a different name.

984
01:27:18,881 --> 01:27:22,840
- The Man of the Stars?
- The Man of the Stars?

985
